 🔑 Authentication vs Authorization:-

## Authentication

Authentication answers:

> **Who are you?**

Authentication verifies the identity of the user.

Examples

- Username
- Password
- Access Keys
- Multi-Factor Authentication (MFA)

---

## Authorization

Authorization answers:

> **What are you allowed to do?**

Authorization determines what AWS resources a user can access.

Examples

- Read S3 Buckets
- Launch EC2 Instances
- Create IAM Users
- Access RDS Databases

Permissions are controlled using **IAM Policies**.

---

# 🔄 Authentication & Authorization Flow

```
User
│
▼
Authentication
(Verify Identity)
│
▼
Authorization
(Check IAM Policies)
│
▼
Access AWS Services
```

---

📌 Best Practices

- Never use the Root User for daily activities.
- Follow the Principle of Least Privilege.
- Use IAM Groups to manage permissions.
- Use IAM Roles for AWS services.
- Enable Multi-Factor Authentication (MFA).
- Rotate access keys regularly.
- Grant only the permissions required.

